Hi @aetna-wsa!

I've never encountered or heard about an issue similar to this one... You might want to have the developers that are having this issue set the `debug` option to `true` and check their console log. Maybe that will shed some light on the problem.

I think as a last resort you could add a `setTimeout` before initializing tablesorter and check to see if tablesorter has initialized and remove the "loading" class. Something like this:

```js
var $wrap = $('#table-sorter'),
    $loader = $('#loader'),
    $table = $('#mytable');

setTimeout(function(){
    if ( $table[0].hasInitialized ) {
        $wrap.removeClass('loading');
        $loader.hide();
    }
}, 3000);

$table.tablesorter({
    // ...
    initialized: function(){
        $wrap.removeClass('loading');
        $loader.hide();
    }
});
```

