@camilonova I think we should support Python 2.7 if we support a Django version that supports it. Python 2.7 will be deprecated in 1.5 years so I don't think we should explicitly drop support from the code base before that. The wait for Python 3 only is not that long now in mid-2018, anyway.

There are a lot of projects using Python 2.7 and if we can support those in our codebase with few simple __future__ and backport imports we should IMO do that.

This is just my philosophy. I think that libraries that have large user bases should support different language versions if it isn't a big stretch, and in this specific case it isn't.

